The easier way is to render the JSON as a String, then get the length:

    int calculateSize(JsonNode jsonNode) throws JsonProcessingException {
        var objectMapper = new ObjectMapper();
        var string = objectMapper.writeValueAsString(jsonNode);
        return string.length();
    }

This operation can be time/memory consuming, since the full JSON content need to be rendered as a `String`.

A better approach is to use a recursive function to traverse the JSON node adding up the total size:

    int calculateSize(JsonNode jsonNode) {
        if (jsonNode == null) {
            return 4; // null
        }
        if (jsonNode.isTextual()) {
            return 2 + jsonNode.asText().length(); // two quotes + string
        }
        if (jsonNode.isArray() || jsonNode.isObject()) {
            var size = new AtomicInteger(2); // square/curly brackets
            if (jsonNode.isObject()) {
                jsonNode.fieldNames().forEachRemaining(
                        field -&gt; size.getAndAdd(3 + field.length())); // quoted key and colon
            }
            if (!jsonNode.isEmpty()) {
                size.getAndAdd(jsonNode.size() - 1); // commas
                jsonNode.elements().forEachRemaining(
                        element -&gt; size.getAndAdd(calculate(element))); // recurs
            }
            return size.get();
        }
        return jsonNode.asText().length(); // boolean, number
    }

This method will traverse the JSON content, but the memory consumption will be minimal.

&gt; Note: some implementations can differ when rendering JSON, e.g., in Javascript, numbers with scientific notation can have different lengths than the equivalent in Java.

